<br>
As her blood filled the soil, something beneath it stirred. Bones lost and discarded soaked in the blood. Sinew and ligament tightened. With every drop that found the corpse, a bit of decay and rot peeled away, as long dead flesh found new life. Suddenly the earth around the dying Koada exploded and the rotting remains of a Teir'dal sneered and drug itself closer toward her.<br>
<br>
Desperately she tried to get away, tried to crawl to safety, but it was on her in seconds. The last thing she heard as bony claws ripped into the flesh of her neck, was a raspy unnatural voice beckoning in Teir'dal: &quot;Scream for me.&quot;<br>
<br>
Through the course of the night it prayed on them, the Koada that guarded the teleportation point. With every kill the death faded away. Dry bones were wrapped in rippling muscle. The remnants of flesh grew and expanded, covering the whole of the body again. Hair and nails were the last things to return. When at last his work was done the warrior stumbled through the forest, southward until at last he collapsed at the river. <br>
<br>
The sharp sting of the cold water filled him with long lost sensation. Dipping his hands in again, he felt a stinging pain as teeth tore flesh. In a second his other hand had a hold of the piranah and was slamming it against rocks on the<br>
shore. <br>
<br>
After a meal of fresh fish, he made his way back to the teleport, avoiding anything and everything along the way. Quickly he stripped the bodies, tearing the robes and rearranging them, making them look less Koada. When at last he was done he stumbled toward Neriak.<br>
<br>
He had no trouble entering the city. As far as the guards and citizens knew, he did not exist. In the foreign quarter he found it, a stash of weapons and armor he had hidden there long ago. They weren't¹t the best but they would do.<br>
<br>
Armed and armored, it was time to begin his training. It had been a long time, his body needed to remember itself, what it could do, how far it could be pushed. Before he could begin though, he needed a drink. Sitting at the bar, an inquisitive patron approached him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ain¹t seen you about,&quot; he said, obviously looking the warrior up and down. &quot;New about these parts?&quot;<br>
<br>
The warrior did not look up from his drink. &quot;I have been gone a very long time.&quot;<br>
<br>
Curiosity peeked the inquisitor continued, &quot;Oh? And what brings you here now?&quot;<br>
<br>
Slowly the warrior turned his gaze on the patron, steel like eyes drilling into the inquisitor's soul.<br>
<br>
&quot;I seek the one known as Talastius, a minion of Prime Nightmare last I saw him.&quot;<br>
<br>
The patron chuckled. &quot;A minion? Hah, you have been gone long. Talastius Anathema sits as Minister of House Affairs from what I hear.&quot;<br>
<br>
With that the warrior plunked coin on the counter and got up to head out of the tavern. The patron however had more questions and was not yet prepared to let him go.<br>
<br>
&quot;So what do you seek him for anyway? He isn¹t often about these parts.&quot;<br>
<br>
The warrior stopped in his footsteps and turned slowly, a twisted smile contorting his face. In a voice both raspy and distant he spoke, &quot;I seek to kill him.&quot;<br>
<br>
The patron burst out laughing. &quot;You? Kill Anathema? By the gods man who do you think you are?&quot;<br>
<br>
A flash of steel and the patron stumbled back, a knife buried in his throat. The warrior turned and walked toward the door calling back to the dying man, and the barkeep.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am Pherrizt. And he is my son.&quot;<br>
<br>
