 <br>
  Running with long, easy strides, his breathing measured and regular he completed the journey's requirements, intending to bring a towering hill giant thundering along right behind him to occupy the human guards of the bridge to southern Karana. His face crinkles in a flash of amusement, there would be no time for the law enforcing pests to inquire about his cargo..He muses off-topic, even in so dire and pressured of a situation, thinking how Prime ought to have these guards on the payroll.<br>
<br>
  The gruesome nature of young Sylexis' wounds now took prominence in his thoughts. They are savage, vicious, serrated. Not precise strikes, like those a fighter still learning their craft might leave. However, the lady was no novice, on the verge of claiming true mastery of the arts of combat herself. The strikes scream of rage and pain, leading to the conclusion these harms were inflicted with raw malice, meant to cause suffering.<br>
<br>
  Dropping the loose hood of his cloak gains unhindered access to the Keep. Despite searing pains from exertion the pace continues unabated directly into the infirmary. Attendants jump into action, one off to find the most senior cleric on site, the others accepting Sylexis' limp body. Face flushed with sweat and pale, the rogue can do little but gulp air desperately, arms and legs shaking with fatigue. The adepts quickly usher the gasping savage from the room without resistance, he realizes he can only be a distraction now.<br>
<br>
  His eyes narrow with murderous intent, they seem to throb visibly, matching the pulse now infused with fury. A new energy ignites movements returned to their normal smooth efficiency. Even though it is a man that moves among the halls, visible in dim lighting, most servants describe his passing as that of a phantom. The eerie silence without an awkward gate, the fluid motions of avoiding obstructions with no loss of pace , this usually followed by mute shrugs of disbelief.<br>
<br>
  The two trolls take interest at the rapidly approaching darker spot, then relaxing to an actual slouch of ease seeing who approaches. Spehk had stepped into the light as he neared, he smelled the foul brew before the whisper met his ear from right troll. Right troll was very quick, in a panicky scared of repercussions sort of way, to inform the most easy going of the old timers &quot;da Minista's rea*urp*d ding&quot;.<br>
<br>
  Presenting a little knife , wet with something, to right troll's face the quiet man lifted that hand up. When eyes followed and head tilted back, the darkness struck. An overhand left punch connected squarely with the troll's throat, cutting off air and silencing it instantly. Bringing his knife hand down across his body clips the grasping hand of troll number two as predicted, not the wound but the shock of being cut by a Minion causing the lumbering guard to draw back a moment. That was all it got before the convulsing spasms took it, shaking it to it's knees. &quot;He reads too much anyway&quot; he grinds out, turning toward his target.<br>
<br>
  A flick of the wrist produces a small, oddly notched device. Teeth clenched in hate or rage were a strange companion to the calm manner in which the trolls are stepped around as they writhe in silence. A single fluid motion feeds the lock's keyhole and registers a distinct *click*. That same continuing motion gains the rogue the chambers of the Minister of House Affairs. Lifting that same knife, the stamped plate that labels the door is pried right out. Spehk takes the plate and throws it , with vicious force into the desk of Talastius, skipping it off papers right into his chest. <br>
<br>
  Had maybe an eyebrow lifted at this violent intrusion ? &quot;and what the hell does this mean anyway ? &quot; the shadows at the doorway shouted. &quot;Minister of everyone else's affairs, but stay the hell out of my own personal business, is what it should say, isn't that right ?&quot; <br>
<br>
  Chambers suited to a Teir'dal were crossed in two long steps, the now overbearing human leaning forward, fists planted flat on the fine, ornate desktop. Still Talastius would not so much as flinch, as much as he leaned back and to the side easily. &quot;You arrogant, aloof, self-absorbed, haughty sonuvabitch ! &quot; he spouted in ascending volume, finishing by wiping over half of the writing table's contents across the room. <br>
<br>
  &quot;You've compromised this Keep, *and* put it's younger Minions into mortal danger ! AND without so much as a 'hey, watch out , out there you guys' !&quot; <br>
<br>
  Exasperation wins, &quot;Whatever, look whatever the hell, do what you want&quot; the shadow stalker has no real understanding of how incoherent he sounds. This is about where some form of rationale is starting to seep in, somewhere underneath all these frayed emotions truths still exist. Things such as his known respect for the Knight's literacy and library. Starting to feel like a bit of an ass he plans a hasty exit. <br>
<br>
  &quot;Oh, I didn't kill the boys on purpose, maybe you could worry more about business than killing them. I wanted in, they had no chance&quot; <br>
<br>
  Stopping at the door, he looks squarely into Talastius' eyes, &quot;if you want in, for whatever reason. To interrogate, to say 'goodbye' *lips makes a quick jump toward a half-smile*. My objective is not sub-dual. You have ten minutes to get outta that and into field gear.&quot; Not completing a step, the rogue backs up, the tilt of Tal's head indicating he's ready .<br>
<br>
  The human was playful, despite any misery, any despair. He waited four slow, pounding heartbeats, then in a flat and direct voice &quot;Our target's name is Pherizzt&quot; .<br>
